WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.380
Thank you. Adequate Tables? No, We Want Great Tables. That's the name of my talk. It's also

00:00:14.380 --> 00:00:20.160
a true statement. Okay, so tables. They're so great for displaying information. They're

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:24.620
underrated sometimes. I talk to people and they're not really appreciative of tables

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:29.840
as much as I am. They can be awesome. Here's a few that I made. I even showed some of these

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.400
recently in a workshop I gave yesterday. So this one's really nice. The first one here,

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:38.720
I'm going to use my pointer. Look at the stuff it has. It has scientific notation in it. It's

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:44.959
got some units, chemistry even. Great. This is wonderful. This one's even got plots within a

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:52.080
table. Super great stuff. But as good as those are, other people have made even better tables.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:58.240
These are ones I found on the internet. Mine can hold a count of these ones. These are really,

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:03.840
really nice. They're super nicely styled. They have titles, footnotes. Very informational and

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:08.959
beautiful. And so the great thing is all these tables were made with GT. It's a package for

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:14.320
making tables. You can make useful tables for publication, tables for sharing, and importantly,

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:19.760
you can make them look good. So the goal of the talk is to look at the story of GT, sort of like

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:27.839
look back a little bit, discover where we came from, where we're going, and there's lots to it.

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:35.199
So let's dive in. So when GT started, it was in 2018, March 20th. That day is when I started the

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:42.080
GitHub repo. It was a week after I joined the company, which was then RStudio. It was wild.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.440
Back then, there were at least nine table packages for R back in 2018. Great names, too, like Pixie

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:55.360
Dust, Stargazer. Xtable was first released in the year 2000. That goes so far back.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.360
It's wild. There's so many of them. I wasn't, you know, deterred by this. We decided to go for it,

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:07.599
make our own, because why not? We had some goals, too. So these are like the main goals I had before

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:14.479
even starting, or near to. Comprehensive table structuring. So number two, large selection of

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:19.839
functions for formatting values. Three, flexible and easy to use, one hopes. Methods for table

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:23.839
stylings. And we wanted to have table rendering that goes to multiple output types.

00:02:27.039 --> 00:02:33.679
So in secret, I worked on GT for most of 2018, added nearly 60 functions, hitting on those

00:02:33.679 --> 00:02:39.520
topics I just mentioned, those goals. Made it public December 6th. I think that was in

00:02:41.279 --> 00:02:46.160
RStudio Conf. Oh, my God, that goes way back. RStudio Conf back then. That's when we made it

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:51.119
public, just before that. And it was pretty good at that time. This is like a little image I had on

00:02:51.119 --> 00:02:56.320
the readme that showed the API, all the functions that are available. It was not bad for a public

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:03.679
release. So our first goal was, you know, pretty much met comprehensive table structuring. We had

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:08.080
a basic blueprint for a table. We wanted to have things like a header, a footer, some place to put

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:13.360
row labels and, you know, just like tease them apart and, you know, make them composable,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.320
configurable. So we worked on formalizing those components. And in the end, it makes everything a

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:23.919
little bit easier to understand as well. And we eventually solidified our table network. We got

00:03:23.919 --> 00:03:29.759
some nomenclature, like stub, stub head, you know, these are fresh new things. And we really sort of

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:36.240
like tried to really formalize things. And it's pretty good. To this day, we still use it. We

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:40.559
haven't modified it much. I think it really works quite well. So we use this all through the

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:47.279
documentation to explain how this API works. Okay. So our second goal was a large selection of

00:03:47.279 --> 00:03:51.919
functions for formatting values. We wanted to get this package on the track. So we had to meet this

00:03:51.919 --> 00:03:57.759
goal. So we started with these formatters. They all began in FMT. And they're just for formatting

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:02.559
values in the table body. They're super important. They're very fundamental to me. And this is a

00:04:02.559 --> 00:04:08.000
pretty reasonable starter pack of formatters for the track release, which was in March 2020.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:12.720
The weird thing is, it took two years from the start of the package to get it to CRAN. That's a

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:17.119
very long time for any package. It's only because we wanted to really get things right, not because

00:04:17.119 --> 00:04:22.160
I was super slow. I was pretty much working out all the time. Just took our time. That's all it was.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:28.959
And because I'm totally obsessed with formatting functions, we added more in 2021 to 2022.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:35.359
Pretty much almost every release had one new one, except for 0.5, which I was a slacker then. Didn't

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:41.679
do it then. And then the last few releases, there was a large volley of formatters because

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.959
I wanted to do them. But they're really useful. And they're really good. The package is better

00:04:46.959 --> 00:04:52.799
for it. So we had a ton of formatters in the last three releases. So all together,

00:04:52.799 --> 00:04:56.720
the current set of formatters, it covers a ton of formatting tasks. We have 29 of them.

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:02.079
You may need them. You may not need them. But I think at least some people need one of these,

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:08.079
at least one of these. So our third goal was flexible and easy-to-use methods for table

00:05:08.079 --> 00:05:11.920
styling. Table styling is super important. It makes the table look good if you want it to look good.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.679
And one way we had it with the initial release was using the function tab style. That allows you just

00:05:17.679 --> 00:05:23.600
to, you know, anywhere in the table, add a style or multiple styles. Another way, which is also

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:29.519
equally good, is using tab options. Just another way of inserting styles into a table. And then

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:34.880
eventually later, we had in a much later release, we had op stylize be put in. Just a way to theme

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:39.440
a table quickly with one function with very few arguments. It's a good starting, jumping off

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:47.119
ground. And, you know, constantly working on this. So we made improvements to the things we added

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:50.799
along the way. And I think it's kind of important to, you know, improve the features you already

00:05:50.799 --> 00:05:58.640
have in subsequent releases. So because of styling, we could have awesome-looking tables like this.

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:02.720
These are not my tables at all. But they look really good because of, you know, all the styling

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:10.799
possibilities in the package. Okay. The fourth goal was to do really good rendering. Table

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:16.320
rendering to multiple output types. So, you know, the steps are you have an input data table,

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:22.239
GT object. So you use functions to make the table. And then finally, you have to report it, you know,

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:29.040
essentially print it out to an output table. Also, you shouldn't need to have to change your

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:34.320
table code depending on the output type. Whatever context you're in, the code just makes that table.

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:40.720
Whether it's good or bad is another issue. So three output types were targeted initially. HTML,

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:47.679
LaTeX, RTF. HTML support was pretty good on the release. I was pretty satisfied. But LaTeX and

00:06:47.679 --> 00:06:52.559
RTF, they were like half good experimental, you might say. But they were at least there. These

00:06:52.559 --> 00:06:58.720
were the beginnings. You have to start somewhere. So, you know, starting somewhere means that you

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:05.040
finish elsewhere. So we had throughout many other releases, we fixed up, improved LaTeX and RTF.

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:13.119
And even the last release had RTF and LaTeX improvements. And HTML, as good as it is,

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:17.839
we made changes there to make it even better. So we focused on speed of rendering tables

00:07:17.839 --> 00:07:21.200
and, of course, having accessible tables in HTML, which is very important to us.

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:30.160
Later, and because I'm giving you dates here, August 2022, the DocX Word output type was

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:36.239
implemented. And Ellis Hughes, if you're in the room, he's from GSK, he did a huge amount of work

00:07:36.239 --> 00:07:42.320
here to make this really good. I'm forever in debt to him for this. But that was done in, yeah,

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:50.079
2022. And it's great. And we're improving that a lot as well. And looking future-wise, I'm sort

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:55.519
of breaking into the future, we're looking at adding Excel and PowerPoint output as well.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:08:01.920
Mostly because there's super strong demand for Excel output. Like everybody wants it. Why aren't

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:07.440
you doing it, Rich? Come on. Get on it. Do it now. Okay. But we're going to do it soon. I promise

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:13.359
you that. So we met these goals. We had a lot of goals. And we did sort of good. Reasonably good.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:19.760
We're always improving. But as we were developing the package, we also developed new goals. There's

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.760
always more to do. So we got four more. We wanted to make, well, let's go one by one through them.

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:31.839
We wanted to have the package be useful across many disciplines and use cases. So a lot of work

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:37.200
is ensuring that the formatters are really good, that you can format according to your

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:41.599
conventions, whatever field you're in. And we looked at lots of tables from all sorts of fields.

00:08:41.599 --> 00:08:45.840
Like there's just a smattering of the fields there. We tried to see if we can reproduce the

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:52.799
tables, whether there's blockers for people in marine biology, for instance. And identifying

00:08:52.799 --> 00:08:57.599
those, we just made improvements. So we added things like improved format scientific, added

00:08:57.599 --> 00:09:01.919
format parts per if you know it, you need it, and added stuff for chemistry as well.

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:10.559
And we wanted to make sure that GT worked for users all over the world. So a big focus was

00:09:10.559 --> 00:09:15.359
ensuring that, you know, numbers, dates and times, even for words, fit the language and

00:09:15.359 --> 00:09:20.239
the region that you're in or you want to format for. So most formatting functions have a locale

00:09:20.239 --> 00:09:26.080
option. And we support nearly 600 locales. And we always update our code with CLDR guidance.

00:09:26.559 --> 00:09:31.919
CLDR is basically just a repository of localization stuff that is constantly updated.

00:09:31.919 --> 00:09:36.719
It's a Unicode project. We look at that a lot. We try to implement the best stuff from there

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:43.520
into our code. And good documentation. That's like super important to us. We're always trying

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:49.919
to improve our documentation. For instance, we found it super important to have many examples

00:09:50.559 --> 00:09:55.280
for every function in the package. And the idea there is if you land on a certain page,

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:00.479
you find something useful fast, you know, whether it's like descriptive text or some

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:05.119
examples that are close to what you need, you shouldn't have to spend too long to get

00:10:05.119 --> 00:10:10.320
the table you want. And a big thing is we talked to a lot of people in Pharma,

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:15.440
and they have specific needs for building tables. So that's why we added RTF support initially,

00:10:16.559 --> 00:10:21.760
because they use that a lot for Pharma-specific tables. And we also more recently included

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:26.080
functionality for splitting tables across pages for paginated output formats. We're going to

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:33.039
continually improve that. Okay. So looking towards the future, I have a short list of things that we

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:39.599
need for a future GT. Big list here. But I'll just go through them one by one. One big thing is like

00:10:39.599 --> 00:10:44.719
a way to reorder your rows of data within GT so you don't have to do that beforehand, say in

00:10:44.719 --> 00:10:50.320
dplyr. Another thing is footnotes. They're really good right now. But there's many possibilities for

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:56.400
better affixing footnotes where you want them in the table. I mentioned Excel before. It's a

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:01.200
popular file format. So that's definitely going to be in the future. And better table splitting.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:07.599
I also alluded to that way to split tables with more flexibility. Right now, we don't have much

00:11:07.599 --> 00:11:11.200
integration with database tables. If you're just to give GT a database table, I'm not sure what

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:15.119
would happen. Probably nothing good. So we want to ensure that we can at least take in like, say,

00:11:15.119 --> 00:11:22.080
a DuckDB table or some other database table and use it as input for GT. Ways to better style text.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:26.400
Right now, if you have a text-heavy table, you really have to do some pre-planning, pre-work to

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:31.119
make it look good. So I feel like there's some work that can be done there to make that better.

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:37.520
And right now, we have new ways to merge cells, like having I talked about this with lots of

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:42.000
people. Say you have redundant text and you just want to merge it all together and have one label

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.640
somewhere. You can't do that right now. I feel like that should be a thing. So that's a future thing.

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:53.440
We've also been working pretty hard on the great tables Python package.

00:11:54.239 --> 00:12:00.080
Right now, Python doesn't have a thing that's like GT. So we're like, yeah, it was just port over GT

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:06.400
to Python. And we call it great tables. So we started the work for that mid-2022. But it really

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:11.280
started going earlier this year. And again, the goal is to bring all that GT goodness over to the

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:17.280
Python language through that package. And we're in the process of porting all the features while

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:26.400
making it fit in well with the Python ecosystem. So we're working on it. But it's actually really

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:33.440
capable today. Tables made with great tables look pretty close to the ones by analogous GT table

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:38.799
with the same code, really. So these two tables are made with pretty much the same code. Of course,

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:43.280
one in great table code, one GT code. They look kind of the same. If you superimpose them,

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:47.599
you just, you know, they're like the same thing. So basically, our plan is to port over the most

00:12:47.599 --> 00:12:52.400
important features first. So, you know, we did that. These tables look pretty good. But there's

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:55.760
a lot of sort of secondary features that are not in there yet. But they're coming.

